Chlorine is an acute toxin that can cause respiratory distress at relatively low concentrations, and can even cause death at higher concentrations.  The chlorine handling equipment at the WTP was designed to safely contain chlorine but in the event of an accidental chlorine release, a chlorine detection and alarm system will alert personnel at the WTP to the need for an emergency response.

American Water Services, Inc. conducted a process hazard analysis of the chlorine process.  The process hazard analysis team consisted of American Water Services personnel knowledgable in process operation and maintenance and knowledgeable in the process hazard analysis process.  The process hazard analysis team used a "what-if / checklist" technique and recommendations were compiled and are being implemented.

American Water Services, Inc. has developed standard operating procedures (SOPs) that provide system descriptions, specifications and operating steps for the chlorine system.  The SOPs address the start-up, shutdown, inspections, temporary operation, emergency procedures and trouble-shooting.  SOPs to provide for mechanical integrity of the chlorine process equipment rely on manufacturer's recommended approaches.  The RMP contains details of this approach.

Our prevention measures include the use of:

- chlorine detectors and alarms to rapidly alert operators to any problems;
- process safety information to document the safe process design;
- process hazards analyses to evaluate the chemical and process hazards;
- operating procedures to ensure that the sytem is operated safely;
- maintenance, inspection and testing to ensure that the system is maintained according to applicable standards and manufacture's recommendation;
- training, hot work permits (if ever required), contractor safety and employee participation programs to ensure that all employ

ees and contractors working on and around the processes are aware of the hazards, can perform their job duties safely and know the actions to be taken in an emergency;
- management of change and prestartup safety reviews to ensure that changes are documented, analyzed and kept within the design basis;
incident investigation procedure to investigate each incident and "near misses" to determine root causes and make needed safety improvements;
- and periodic safety audits to ensure that our programs are working as they should to protect both employees and the public.

Within the last five years, the Waterbury Water Plant has not had any accidental releases that resulted in injuries or property damage.  The plant has maintained an excellent safety record throughout its operating history and has never had a major chlorine release.

In the event that a chlorine release does occur, the Waterbury Water Plant has an emergency response program that coordinates emergency response with the Local Emergency Planning Committee.  If such a release did occur, plant personnel would contact the local emergency responders (Thomaston Fire Department) who would dispatch a trained HAZMAT team to the site to handle the chlorine release.  For all but minor releases of chlorine, American Water Services, Inc. intends to rely on the Thomaston, Connecticut Fire Department for response to an accidental release of chlorine, including providing incident command, local area evacuation and shelter-in-place notifications and coordination with other appropriate agencies.  American Water Services personnel are responsible for initial notification of the Fire Department of a release and for facility evacuation and accounting for WTP employees in the event of a major chlorine release.

